    en: "NY law tightly regulates credit repair companies — businesses that charge a fee to improve a person's credit report. The rules are at NY General Business Law Article 28-BB (sections 458-a through 458-l), called the Credit Services Business Act. Federal law (the Credit Repair Organizations Act, 15 USC 1679 et seq.) provides parallel protection. Key consumer rights: a written contract before any service, a 5-day right to cancel without penalty, no payment required until services are performed, and no false promises about what the company can do. A credit repair company that promises to remove accurate negative information or to create a 'new identity' is committing fraud. Enforcement comes from the NY Attorney General and the Federal Trade Commission. Most legitimate credit improvement comes from the consumer's own actions, not from a paid service."
